Cedars-Sinai has prioritized risk stratification efforts in order to tailor specific interventions to best meet the needs of our patients. We have also implemented care coordination efforts across the continuum of care, including pre-operative outreach for scheduled procedures, inpatient care coordination with close focus on transitions of care, and telephonic follow-up when a patient is at home or in a post-acute facility. Discharge and self-care education, management of comorbid conditions, and appropriate referrals to supportive care medicine have also all been enhanced. Telehealth developments are in process as we consider how to best implement at Cedars-Sinai. Cedars-Sinai is continuing to evaluate screening tools and methods for engaging community partners for social determinants of health.

In data analysis and feedback, we've partnered with a third-party vendor to allow us to closely monitor performance data for our selected episodes. We also hold regular meetings (both working group and executive review) to discuss the data and plan improvement cycles.
No challenges to meeting the CEHRT use requirements.

We have made great progress on our high priority Care Redesign Interventions, specifically the following: - Coordination with Post-Acute Care Facilities: We have joint operating committee meetings with management teams that own and operate skilled nursing facilities to review BPCI-A patients who were discharged from their facilities and opportunities for continuous improvement.- Helping Address Socioeconomic Barriers to Care: We set up operations for a nurse practitioner to visit BPCI-A patients at their place of residence, allowing us to gain insight into the home and social factors that impact our patients' care. - Multidisciplinary Team-Based Care: We conduct a weekly BPCI-A Working Team Meeting to review BPCI-A patients with a team that includes representation from pharmacy, patient navigators, case management, documentation & coding, nursing, physical therapy, administration, and post-acute care units.

One of the challenges that we have experienced is in coordinating care with primary care providers. Despite NPRA sharing agreements with attending physicians, it has been difficult to motivate them to change their pre-existing referral patterns to post-acute care facilities that we have identified as being high performing institutions.

Some key considerations that we assessed to establish Financial Arrangements include the following: - Alignment with Vendors: We have engaged multiple contracted entities (e.g. health technology firms, post-acute care navigator staffing agency) to support us with the program and need to align incentives with them.  - Mechanism to Incentivize Physicians: We observed that there are many different physicians managing Traditional Medicare patients at our hospital, so we prioritized the physicians who historically saw the most patients specific to the clinical episodes that we selected. For these priority physicians, we established financial arrangements to motivate them to collaborate with our broader efforts to improve care coordination.

In the event a manager departs the organization, the individuals senior manager will oversee all implementation duties in the interim. The senior manager will remove all access for the manager that departed the organization and will update any contact information as necessary. The senior manager will meet with the team involved in the implementation of the BPC Advanced Model to confirm if all deliverables and implementation are on track until an individual is hired and trained.

The initial CMS Beneficiary Notification letter contained our organization  phone number where the beneficiary can call if they had any questions. The theme of the questions we received are :- Beneficiary did not understand the letter and the initiative with Medicare - Beneficiaries wanted to know if there was this an an additional cost to them - Some beneficiaries reported, that when speaking with someone at Medicare to get more information about the model, the person with Medicare were not aware of the initiative.

Sound has developed a data analytic platform and clinical integration strategy to monitor and mitigate unintended consequences for our BPCIA patients.  We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

Hip Fractures: Working on standardizing care pathway across the care continuum, including engaging PAC partners in driving quality and outcomes. Initial meetings with PAC partners have taken place (3 meetings x 2 partners) to launch into this work. Hip Fracture care pathway mapping and redesign project has launched. The theme of the questions we received are :- Beneficiary did not understand the letter and the initiative with Medicare - Beneficiaries wanted to know if there was this an an additional cost to them - Some beneficiaries reported, that when speaking with someone at Medicare to get more information about the model, the person with Medicare were not aware of the initiative.

Sound has developed a data analytic platform and clinical integration strategy to monitor and mitigate unintended consequences for our BPCIA patients.  We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

ICS combines a people-driven and technology-driven care coordination model to redesign care. The primary priority for implementation has been a significant investment in a technology product which ICS has built from scratch to enable, optimize and improve the nurses in the field who are actively managing patients and working alongside care teams. Secondly, ICS continues to enhance our clinical assessments and risk assessments to enable auto-populated 90-day care plans that are based on evidence-based guidelines, symptoms management/identification and expected outcomes - there has been significant enhancements to the clinical care model and 90-day care plans in 2019. Finally, ICS works closely with hospital(s) to transform the hospital discharge planning process which is an ongoing effort and involves everything from determining optimal first PAC setting of care to ensuring patients are treated in the highest quality providers in the market.

ICS BPID 1191 experienced a significant change in practicing hospital by our PGP partners shifting almost completely from one hospital provider to another during BPCI-A implementation. This has required significant operational and implementation effort to bring the new hospital leadership and key physicians onboard with the BPCI-A program and meaningfully engage in care redesign efforts. Additionally, this has resulted in unknown target prices given this change throughout the performance period, leaving ICS with a significant "blindspot" around projected results via the monthly claims files received to date.

We fully align with our partners through NPRA sharing agreements which recognize the unique and direct role each individual partner plays in specific areas of care redesign which is tied to well-defined metrics under each of our direct influence.

- We have worked closely with physicians and other members of an interdisciplinary team to establish and implement a diagnosis- triggered clinical care pathway for the episode. The spinal fusion, non-cervical care pathway extends from the decision for surgery through the 90 day episode. SNF pathways have also been developed and implemented with our system SNFs. - We have introduced a care navigator into the care pathway for the episode patients. The care navigator follows the patient through their episode of care. Preadmission care navigation for the episode patients includes identifying and mitigating risks, educating the patient and family about the procedure, and preparing for discharge. The care navigator addresses some socio-economic barriers to care, including medication affordability, caregiver support, health literacy and transportation, discharge planning. -We have focused on patient engagement and shared decision making for the spinal fusion non-cervical bundle through the inclusion of a mandatory educational class for patient and caregiver. The class is  embedded within preadmission testing. This has resulted in patients being more prepared for surgery, including being fitted in advance for any required bracing to encourage early ambulation within the inpatient stay.-During inpatient stays, we use structured patient communication boards in patient rooms and structured inpatient rounding by managers. -Any readmissions are reviewed by an interdisciplinary group including physicians to address opportunities for improvement.

Our biggest challenge is that we have relatively low volume, and therefore greater risk of variation. However, we took on this program with the belief that it is important to learn how to manage care across the episode.

We have done a nice job keeping track of these patients while they are in the hospital and getting them in to see a primary care provider or other specialist within a week. Our care coordinators are monitoring these patients after discharge with good engagement from most patients.

Identifying which patients will eventually be part of the bundle with precision has been challenging. In response, we have been notifying any patient that may fall into it, which has resulted in us notifying a lot of patients about the bundle unnecessarily. We haven't had as many episodes as we have historically, partially due to variation and partially as a result of more accurate coding, which has resulted in more precise DRGs being used more frequently, and thus fewer of these particular episodes. It has been challenging keeping close tabs on the post-discharge care setting usage rather than sending them to a post-acute facility by default. This has led to higher Medicare spending on these patients than we anticipated.

Our structure and existing programs weighed heavily in our decision. All of our providers are directly employed by our hospital entity, not contracted as a separate group, and we already have an incentive mechanism in place that is tied to our performance on cost and quality in our full portfolio of value-based programs. We determined that setting up a separate incentive infrastructure specific to a single program would be duplicative and prohibitive to participating in the program.

Our Population Health Steering Committee oversees all of our value-based programs, so there are always multiple people knowledgeable about the program. If the executive overseeing it were to leave, there is another layer of management involved that could pick up tasks as needed. Those people have access to the portals and documents that would be needed to manage the required tasks as part of participation. We also have interdisciplinary working groups that report to the Steering Committee which are comprised of people knowledgeable about the program that could step in to perform tasks and/or lead initiatives if needed.

A few patients have complained that they are uneasy about it simply because they receive so many documents on admission, so it's easy to get confused, particularly in the case of the conditions we're participating in (AMI and Cardiac Arrhythmia). It's not frequent but it has come up from time to time. It's unclear whether or not it has any real value to the patient.

If nothing else, we have learned quite a bit about ourselves and our own facility by participating in the program. We assume that payment models like this will be mandatory in the future, so we're using this voluntary time to learn how to succeed. Higher spend than we had hoped which may result in repayment by us to CMS is an unexpected negative outcome that we anticipate as a possibility, but we're unsure of that at this point until we get an official reconciliation.

Nothing significant; sometimes it's difficult knowing what exactly needs to be done and getting clarification around that. As noted earlier in this questionnaire, we had an LBN change recently that was submitted to CMS via PECOS, but didn't carry over to this CMMI program. We didn't realize that until just now, so we'll get that submitted separately and taken care of. But it is a duplication given that we notified CMS through another channel. Anything that can be streamlined related to documentation is greatly appreciated.

We occasionally submit emails to the BPCI mailbox. It would be helpful to have a phone option/helpline as well for more urgent questions, or to explain complicated questions more easily and add context. The MSSP has this and it has proven to be helpful, especially when time is of the essence. It would also be helpful to have a calendar showing when official reports will be issued (especially reconciliation reports). Vague deadlines such as "this fall" aren't as helpful for planning purposes (report-out meetings, etc.). The MSSP has a calendar which has been helpful and probably generates fewer emails to CMS asking about the timing.

Santa Rosa's high priority Care Redesign Intervention was around shared decision-making, specifically pertaining to the pre-operative and 90 day post-acute time frame.  In addition to the current Total Joint Patient Navigator, a new role entitled the "Bundled Payment Care Manager" was created.  The focus of the Bundled Payment Care Manager is to guide and coordinate high and rising risk patients through multiple care delivery systems, with emphasis on training the providers and downstream episode participants (SNF, Home Care, OP Physical Therapy) on implementation of patient risk screening/risk mitigation tools, in addition to engaging patient's family/caregiver/coach in the decision making process.

Success around our Care Redesign Interventions are evident in the increased communication across the entire care continuum.  Whether it's a phone call from an Outpatient Physical Therapist with a concern around a total knee patient's range of motion, or a Saturday evening call from a SNF requesting assist to help avoid a patient readmission, our increased communication is audible!  Challenges/barriers arise with our extensive geographic reach and rural settings which make it even more evident that our strategy around the Bundled Payment Care Manager role being necessary for the pre-operative optimization of the patient and the success of the overall program in terms of outcomes, readmission reduction and patient satisfaction.

Further, would appreciate more specific language around "Participating Practitioners", to supply a more specific response.

Challenges would include short turn around times for large healthcare systems; complicated forms and data requests; too frequent of requests. Also, a continuous challenge is the overlap of all CMS models, and unclear compliance requirements.

Santa Rosa Memorial Hospital is participating in BPCI-A for Lower Extremity Joint Replacement and Upper Extremity Joint Replacement.  The main challenges that we have found with the Lower Extremity Joint Replacement cohort is that hip fracture/hemiarthroplasty patients are included in this group.  Although risk adjusted, the majority of this patient population is high acuity and requires great resources (lengthy hospital LOS, extended SNF stays, multiple comorbidities, higher incidence of readmission) and as a result, this non-elective population is straining the target bundle price. Our recommendation or ask would be that for this Clinical Episode, as with all BPCI-A Clinical Episodes, CMS apply a target price per DRG, and possibly even broken out by (in this case) w/ and w/o fractures. This would account for the patient acuity, and be more appropriate.

On the whole, our practice is on track to meet our high priority care redesign areas.  We have focused our care redesign efforts on consolidating order sets by disease states among three different EMRs with the goal of reducing variation while also improving quality and decreasing cost.  Additionally, we are redesigning post-discharge care through the use of a care management program, a transitions clinic, TCM/discharge follow up visits, and development of a post-acute network of vested partners.  We have also implemented a community referral system to address socioeconomic barriers.

Coinciding with the implementation of this model, our system went through a merger of two distinct healthcare systems. We have and still are experiencing the usual growing pains that accompany such a substantial change.  While this process might have presented its own distinct challenges, it has also given us a unique platform for messaging the importance of value-based care and the importance it plays in the decisions we are making.

Our Primary POC/Primary Data POC oversees implementation of the model and if they were to depart from the organization, our Secondary Data POC would assume implementation responsibilities with oversight from our Secondary POC.

We routinely review various sources of data at both an aggregate and patient-level for effects of our decisions around care redesign e.g. how shifts in site of post-acute care impacts readmission rates.

Our episode selection strategy has resulted in some Episode Initiator/Episode Type combinations that are resulting in low volumes and thus limiting our ability to identify true opportunities.  We will rethink our strategy for Cohort #2, considering both increasing the number of Episode Initiators for each Episode Type or only participating in those with high volume.

We used our experience in BPCI Classic to review the historical data sets and develop a financial structure that rewarded program adherence, improvement in clinical outcomes for beneficiaries, and coordination of care transition activities.

We have secured a secondary repayment line of credit from our financial institution in the event that negative repayment amounts are necessary. Signature Care Management has a structured orientation and training program for all employees, including management. We also focus on cross-training of key activities and tasks, to ensure redundancy of systems and knowledge transfer. In addition, we employ a management structure that plans for, and encourages development and promotion from within in the event of key employee departures.

SMG promotes an open line of communication between the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer and all Model Participants. Any Model Participant may seek clarification from the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer on any issue where there is confusion or questions regarding policies and procedures. SMG has established a policy of confidentiality and non-retaliation when any individual reports or discusses matters with the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer involving potential violations of law, including but not limited to, potential fraud or abuse. The BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer will be responsible for monitoring the Model for compliance with applicable laws and regulations and the CMS Agreement. Audits for compliance may be conducted by the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer or, as appointed by the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer, outside auditors, or consultants. All Model Participants are expected to fully cooperate with any audits or reviews conducted.

In addition, we employ a management structure that plans for, and encourages development and promotion from within in the event of key employee departures.

SMG promotes an open line of communication between the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer and all Model Participants. Any Model Participant may seek clarification from the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer on any issue where there is confusion or questions regarding policies and procedures. SMG has established a policy of confidentiality and non-retaliation when any individual reports or discusses matters with the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer involving potential violations of law, including but not limited to, potential fraud or abuse. The BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer will be responsible for monitoring the Model for compliance with applicable laws and regulations and the CMS Agreement. Audits for compliance may be conducted by the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer or, as appointed by the BPCI Advanced Compliance Officer, outside auditors, or consultants. All Model Participants are expected to fully cooperate with any audits or reviews conducted.

Tucson Orthopaedics has a long history as a convener in BPCI Classic and is comfortable taking measured risk in certain orthopedic bundles.  The structure of financial arrangements from BPCI Classic carried over seamlessly to BPCI Advanced.

Tucson Orthopedics utilizes Stryker Performance Solutions to track and administer processes related to shared repayment amounts.  Shared repayment parameters are as follows for the non-convener and downstream gainsharing physicians:If the Repayment Amount or Excess Spending Amount for a Performance Period exceeds the amount available in the Reserve Pool at the time of the initial Reconciliation, Participant shall be responsible for 40% of the remaining amount owed to CMS, with Participating Practitioners responsible for the other 60% (the Practitioner Share). The percentage of the Practitioner Share that must be paid by each Participating Practitioner as a Shared Repayment Amount will be the proportion of the total Repayment Amount (or Excess Spending Amount generated by such Participating Practitioners Episodes of Care during the Performance Period as compared to the Repayment Amount or Excess Spending Amount generated by all Episodes of Care during the Performance Period.
Tucson Orthopaedics is a large PGP non-convener and an impressive administrative team and clinicians devoted to BPCI Advanced. Succession planning is not an issue.

Patients receive a paper copy of the beneficiary notification form to in their pre-op educational packet prior to surgery.  Beneficiary notification is also provided electronically via RecoveryCOACH, Stryker Performance Solution's web based patient engagement and care management platform.

Medicare claims provided are monitored monthly for trends including readmission rates, emergency room use (diagnosis, day of the week, etc.), and complications.  If a negative trend is identified, the information is communicated back to all parties so that an action plan can be put into place. Participating physicians are routinely reminded that insufficient care may lead to higher cost and that the right care at the right time typically leads to cost reduction.

- New templates are provided by CMS every quarter for quarterly deliverables with little to no noticeable change- Documents have to be submitted quarterly regardless of whether there is no change from the previous submission- There is typically very little time given to complete a large set of deliverables with very little advanced warning.

Confluence Health and Wenatchee Valley Medical Group are working to implement care pathways for cardiac arrythmia and stroke. This process is informed by our experience implementing care pathways for total joint replacement (knee and hip replacement), coronary artery bypass grafting, spinal fusion and acute myocardial infarction care. Our efforts are focused on creating standard processes in four cycles of care: (1) appropriateness requirements for diagnosis and a trial of nonsurgical care, (2) requirements for fitness for surgery, including documented shared decision making and evaluation of the patients social risks, (3) elements of best practice of surgery, and (4) components for rapid return to function, inclusive of the transition from inpatient to outpatient or home care. Each cycle is guided by current clinical evidence and improvements based on results within each cycle, as tracked by a guiding team for the care pathway. Case managers are assigned to each patient to ensure appropriate transition throughout the pathway and effective beneficiary engagement, and a physician oversight team reviews cases that are deemed challenging for disposition or that fall out due to outcomes not meeting goals.

Confluence Health is a convener, but its two Downstream Episode Initiators are the two hospitals owned by Confluence Health: Central Washington Hospital and Wenatchee Valley Medical Center. There is not really a need to monitor agreements between Confluence Health and the two hospitals, because they are all led by the same management team.

Our Care redesign has added a priority of case managers onsite at partner providers (SNFs particularly) to meet with the patient and clinical team to collaborate on appropriate care, planning and discharge strategies for each patient specific to their needs within Medicare guidelines for skilled need.  We have also reformulated our technology platform to enhance how our partner providers provide patient information so we have more timely access to functional status and social work discharge planning information.

Barriers to our success with Care Redesign continues to be post-acute providers who do not provide timely transition and do not adhere to medicare guidelines regarding transition of care.  Also, patients and families who feel entitled to benefits while not understanding the necessary certification for medical necessity.  They feel the surgeon's team is not allowing them to have the care they feel they deserve, rather than understand that they may not qualify for the benefit.   Last, primary care physicians and hospitals who participate in conflicting ACOs or BPCI-A programs themselves who do not adhere to the surgeon's preferences or care plan outlined with the patient pre-operatively, referring patients to poorly performing and/or high cost providers.

IBJI and its PGP partners do not believe in less care. Our program approach is built on coordinated care that delivers the medically appropriate standard of safe and high quality interventions on an individualized basis.  Protocol based care can be manipulated. We assign functional progression markers to all of our Care Plans that requires the appropriate duration and intensity of care at all times throughout the full continuum of recovery.First, through the facilitation of IBJI's Orthopaedic Director, Chief Medical Officer, all surgeons will establish a consistent template of care through the electronic health record. This will create a consistent standard of care across IBJI and its partner PGPs that will be shared with our participating partners. Second, we have an active and engaged Quality Assurance Committee comprised of IBJI physician leaders (all interested physicians may attend), the individual service line team leaders and participating PGP organization leaders chaired by our IBJI Orthopaedic Director, Chief Medical Officer. This Quality Assurance Committee meets quarterly to review quality data collected for trending and benchmarking analysis. Reviewed are:    Variations from the established patient protocols;     Comparative clinical and functional outcomes among our contracted partner and non-partner providers: Patient outlier outcomes and adverse event trends Over-utilization and underutilization patterns of service utilization; Patient satisfaction survey and patient call results concerning the patient experience. Third, we provide quarterly quality data to our with our post-acute partner network providers to review individual and aggregate patient results and/or trends impacting patient outcomes. Finally, a quarterly summary report and webinar is held with all our participating surgeons to review and discussion BPCI-A data supported by our BPCI management team.

We have implemented spinal fusion patient dashboards using internal clinical and billing data and merged this data set with CMS raw historical and monthly claims data.  These data were central to redesigning transitional care pathways.  Stakeholders and care teams within the Spinal Fusion Episode of Care Team have implemented pathways to ensure more accurate and timely information around discharge, enabling the Transition of Care teams to plan for appropriate care needs post-discharge.

As anticipated we uncovered variations with patient education and care team discharge planning.  The creation of the Spinal Fusion Episode of Care team comprised of surgeons, MSHMC transitional care team, post-acute care admin, , nurses, social workers, and therapists has helped establish core principals to reduce variations across the two service lines that care for this patient population.  PSH and MSHMC have begun testing the impact of the multidisciplinary care protocols for all spinal fusion (non-cervical) patients and recently have seen changes in discharge disposition rates in performance period two.

There has been significant progress in the care transitions process.  During the inpatient stay, all bundle patients are identified as early as possible and are assigned the appropriate educational materials.  A Care Transitions Assistant facilitates the scheduling of post discharge follow up appointments for heart failure and acute myocardial infarction patients.  Future plans include expansion of telehealth visits and use of remote patient monitoring for the heart failure patient population.A COPD Care Transitions RN monitors the inpatient stay of COPD patients and ensures a post discharge appointment is scheduled.  The COPD Care Transitions RN follows patients with follow up telephone calls post discharge.  A distress survey and risk scoring methodology is used for COPD patients that need urgent follow up and/or intervention.  In close collaboration with the COPD Care Transitions RN and clinical team, Lay Navigation is used for this patient population. Structured communication has been developed through the creation of discharge forms by the Care Transitions team and are stored in the electronic health record.  Additionally, EHR messaging for urgent communication needs is used among all UAB providers.  HealtheCare communication is used by the Care Transitions team and a post discharge electronic phone call series is administered to all bundle patients that triggers a nurse follow up as needed.

Two high-priority elements of our care design included development of episode-specific clinical pathways and improving clinical decision support for BPCI-A activities with in our new EMR (launched 5/1/2019).  We have developed clinical pathways for our newest clinical episodes within BPCI-A, most notably for patients with cellulitis, collaborating closely with our Infectious Disease specialist to ensure these patients are on the appropriate antibiotics and have close medical follow-up after discharge from the hospital to prevent re-hospitalizations.  We have strengthened clinical pathways built in BPCI Model 2 for patients with CHF which now serves as the standard of care for all patients with CHF admitted to our hospital.  Optimization of our new EMR includes implementation of the LACE tool to assess risk for readmission in all patients and hardwiring tracking codes for advanced care planning.

Closer alignment with the Infectious Disease specialist has led to fewer readmissions within clinical episodes for cellulitis.  However, when a patient's cellulitis is related to opioid use disorder (OUD) and despite robust efforts to improve initiation and engagement in treatment for OUD, these patients often leave against medical advice and readmit to the hospital.  In clinical episodes for GI Hemorrhage our team reports that patients are often taking anticoagulants and that these typically contribute to and often complicate GI Hemorrhage, creating challenges for management throughout the episode.  Finally, our team is most proud of outcomes achieved after managing clinical episodes for CHF since 2015, namely reducing readmissions to LGH from 22% in 2017 to 20% in 2018 and17% in 2019 to-date.

We elected to use all waivers but have not been able to operationalize all waivers for various reasons.  For example, the Home Visit Waiver only allows for a participant-employed provider to conduct a post-discharge home visit.  The providers we work with who could conduct a home visit are not employed by the hospital, so we have not been able to operationalize this waiver.  We have experience utilizing the SNF waiver in other alternative payment models but have not needed to utilize it for any of the patients within our BPCI-A program since 10/2018.  To-date we have explored but not operationalized any telehealth program that could be utilized under the Telehealth waiver.

Our BPCI-A team is small, consisting of the Director of Population Health, Director of Integrated Care, two dedicated RN Care Managers, and the Medical Director of Population Health.  Our extended team consists of a PT Care Manager who follows patients in SNFs and the Palliative Care team, Case Managers, Clinical Care Coordinators, Hospitalists and other clinicians and hospital leaders.  We experienced turnover within this team during participation in BPCI Model 2 and were successful at onboarding new team members to our documented processes through 1:1 training and participation in working group meetings focused on readmissions, quality, and population health.

All patients who could potentially be included in BPCI-A are followed very closely by our RN Care Managers and extended team. We monitor daily patient activity for any readmissions and respond accordingly to understand the drivers of readmission, we case conference several times per week with our preferred VNA (who is also our NPRA Sharing Partner), we participate in multidisciplinary rounds daily to ensure patients are receiving the right care at the right time and have appropriate discharge plans in place, and we meet with patients fact-to-face during their anchor admission to ensure they understand their care, understand any patient teaching, have follow-up appointments scheduled, and have transportation to those follow-up appointments.  Our Palliative Care team is actively engaged to ensure that patients and their families have an opportunity to discuss goals of care and complete advanced care planning paperwork.  Finally, LGH is a mission-driven hospital providing care to an underserved population and is always committed to doing the right thing for each patient, regardless of payment source or arrangement.

Due dates for deliverables can be confusing and notification is not consistently sent to the dedicated person.  For example, notification about this questionnaire indicated that LGH would not be in the first cohort of participants expected to complete and return the questionnaire, but a notice that the questionnaire was past due was then sent to the VP overseeing population health but not the dedicating person within population health.  Also, questions about specific deliverables, most notably the QPP list, were not immediately or clearly answered, creating some confusion and potential delays.

The greatest challenge has been identification of beneficiaries who will ultimately be included in a given clinical episode.  Final DRGs are not assigned until discharge and working DRGs are not always accurate.  We have had no visibility into which beneficiaries are in an ACO or MSSP arrangement (and thus excluded), and remain unclear about when ESRD does or does not exclude beneficiaries from a clinical episode.  The frustration associated with this, and the daily task of identifying patients, can lead to burnout among members of the team.  A second significant challenge has been that clinical episode volume is much lower than in BPCI Model 2 and much lower than predicted primarily due to the exclusion of beneficiaries involved in an ACO or MSSP, and the proliferation of these programs in the region.  Lower patient volumes in each clinical episode make achievement of savings much more difficult, increase the hospital's risk, and decrease likelihood of continuing in the program.

Successes: Working directly with local resources, we have assisted patients in procuring housing, adequate food and transportation critical to an optimal clinical outcome. Since October 1, 2018, care redesign initiatives have focused on ensuring that patients receive the right care, for the right reason, and for the right period of time during their episode of care.  This has meant assessing preoperative risk to drive optimization prior to surgery as well as purposeful comprehensive patient care management during the post-acute phase.  Care redesign is largely complete but will be ongoing throughout the program.

One of the biggest challenges with implementing care redesign is tracking progress and sharing information with pertinent parties.  Stryker has very successfully put in place systems to track progress in real time while utilizing retrospective claims data to drive actionable improvement.

One recent challenge with regard to executing agreements within Stryker's convener is executing non-financially based agreements with physicians and or non-physician practitioners.  There is very little reason from their perspective to spend their time reviewing, making potential changes to, and executing an agreement of this nature.  When an episode initiator is a hospital who has chosen not to gainshare financially downstream but is now required as of Q4 2019 to have non-financial participation agreements in place, it is very burdensome.
NA: System already in place before this model
NA; we don't have relationship with a BPCI Advanced Entity

As far as Stryker is concerned, financial arrangements and the ability to share savings is key to the success of bundled payment models.  It allows pertinent parties to align around shared vision and goals.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing
NA; not requiring shared repayments by partners

Stryker is a large BPCI Advanced convener and Performance Solutions has an impressive team of subject matter experts and consultants devoted solely to BPCI Advanced. When combined with our actuarial and analytics team, Stryker has approximately 60 staff members devoted to the program.  Succession planning is not an issue.

Most PGPs in Stryker's convener have chosen to provide a paper copy of the beneficiary notification form to patients in a pre-op educational packet prior to surgery.  Beneficiary notification is also provided electronically via RecoveryCOACH, Stryker's web based patient engagement and care management platform.

Medicare claims provided are monitored monthly for trends including readmission rates, emergency room use (diagnosis, day of the week, etc.), and complications.  If a negative trend is identified, the information is communicated back to all parties so that an action plan can be put into place. Episode initiators are routinely reminded that insufficient care may lead to higher cost and that the right care at the right time typically leads to cost reduction.

- New templates are provided by CMS every quarter for quarterly deliverables with little to no noticeable change- Documents have to be submitted quarterly regardless of whether there is no change from the previous submission- There is typically very little time given to complete a large set of deliverables.  This questionnaire is an example of that.  We have 2 weeks to submit the questionnaire and 3 corresponding documents for 70+ episode initiators, all with separate BPIDs and participation agreements.
NA; we didn't have any changes

Stryker is a large BPCI Advanced convener and Performance Solutions has an impressive team of subject matter experts and consultants devoted solely to BPCI Advanced. When combined with our actuarial and analytics team, Stryker has approximately 60 staff members devoted to the program.  Succession planning is not an issue.

Most PGPs in Stryker's convener have chosen to provide a paper copy of the beneficiary notification form to patients in a pre-op educational packet prior to surgery.  Beneficiary notification is also provided electronically via RecoveryCOACH, Stryker's web based patient engagement and care management platform.

Medicare claims provided are monitored monthly for trends including readmission rates, emergency room use (diagnosis, day of the week, etc.), and complications.  If a negative trend is identified, the information is communicated back to all parties so that an action plan can be put into place. Episode initiators are routinely reminded that insufficient care may lead to higher cost and that the right care at the right time typically leads to cost reduction.

This questionnaire is an example of that.  We have 2 weeks to submit the questionnaire and 3 corresponding documents for 70+ episode initiators, all with separate BPIDs and participation agreements.

Since October 1, 2018, care redesign initiatives have focused on ensuring that patients receive the right care, for the right reason, and for the right period of time during their episode of care.  This has meant assessing preoperative risk to drive optimization prior to surgery as well as purposeful comprehensive patient care management during the post-acute phase.  Care redesign is largely complete but will be ongoing throughout the program.

One of the biggest challenges with implementing care redesign is tracking progress and sharing information with pertinent parties.  Stryker has very successfully put in place systems to track progress in real time while utilizing retrospective claims data to drive actionable improvement.

One recent challenge with regard to executing agreements within Stryker's convener is executing non-financially based agreements with physicians and or non-physician practitioners.  There is very little reason from their perspective to spend their time reviewing, making potential changes to, and executing an agreement of this nature.  When an episode initiator is a hospital who has chosen not to gainshare financially downstream but is now required as of Q4 2019 to have non-financial participation agreements in place, it is very burdensome.

Sutter Health's planned care improvement interventions for BPCI-A care episodes incorporate Lean process redesign to achieve better patient outcomes, higher patient satisfaction, and Medicare fee-for-service cost savings by improving care coordination and implementing more efficient, collaborative care. To date, Sutter's analysis of episodes of care within our system has revealed process variability in the utilization of skilled-nursing and acute-rehabilitation services that does not appear to be related to patient characteristics.Participation in the BPCI-A program is enabling Sutter to reexamine all aspects of episodic care, from pre-operative patient education through post-discharge home health and outpatient therapy, to standardizeour processes for ensuring each patient receives the appropriate level of post-acute care throughout the clinical episode.

Care Redesign interventions often involve third-party partnerships and collaborations, such as establishing standard orders with a diverse range of clinicians and post-acute care management protocols. While these collaborations are worthwhile, these also take time to achieve consensus and broad adoption.
The timeline for the BPCI Advanced Model has been significantly tight in terms of data availability, participation determination, episode selections, and establishing partner agreements.

A crucial consideration in establishing Financial Arrangements has been the fact that episode initiating physicians have expected upside-only arrangements in the current business environment, where the hospital systems face competition from private equity companies (as conveners) and physician groups themselves (as either conveners or non-conveners). This reality has presented challenges to effective alignment with episode initiators.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing
Sutter Health has hired a claims analytics vendor to assist with performance period reconciliations and NPRA calculations, including Shared Repayment Amounts.

To be clear, Sutter Health is not using MPP Waivers, but we are using the Fraud & Abuse waivers. Our compliance program would audit any sharing payment for compliance with the Fraud & Abuse, noting again we are not using the Medicare Payment Policy Waivers at this time.

Sutter Health has established an Executive Steering Committee to lead and monitor the BPCI Advanced program. This team of senior executives has direct accountability for the various functional areas necessary to effectively perform in value-based care and these senior executives provide an inherent succession plan to ensure ongoing engagement in this program.Furthermore, Sutter Health has a well-established succession planning process and tools to support leadership development and effectiveness across all functional areas within the enterprise.

Some Medicare beneficiaries are confused by the requirement to furnish the Beneficiary Notification Letter (BNL), as a subset of patients have considered this document a potential indication of substandard care as determined by CMS. Simply put, the BNL is confusing for some beneficiaries.

Each hospital team has formed workgroups to monitor current performance and discuss opportunities for variation reduction that aligns with the design of the BPCI Advanced program. This variation reduction work includes identifying and addressing unintended consequences associated with the implementation of the BPCI Advanced Model.
The timeline to respond to CMS documentation requirements is a challenge for a system this size, especially in light of the numerous stakeholders involved in a program with this scope.

Michigan Medicine continues to pursue sharing unblinded provider-level data with providers and teams in a variety of settings. Specifically related to BPCI Advanced, Michigan Medicine has started sharing unblinded discharge disposition data with surgeons in order to identify outliers and change culture around discharge disposition. There is interest in sharing similar data with Hospital Medicine physicians in order to impact discharge disposition for medical bundles as well. Michigan Medicine continues to pursue internal cost accounting. Cost drivers have been identified through close observations and time studies, and labor and supply costs are currently being validated. Costing reports have been developed for a select number of conditions, and data will be live for the entire institution in early 2020. Michigan Medicine is still in the pilot phase for collecting Patient-Reported Outcomes Measures (PROMs) with Orthopedic Surgery. Michigan Medicine still plan to roll out this process to the entire institution with generic PROM questionnaires, but the process has been delayed due to a change in physician champion.

The challenges of implementing care redesign interventions at Michigan Medicine are often related to the pace of implementation. Michigan Medicine is a large, integrated health system and we implement interventions in a payer-agnostic manner. This results in more sustainable and meaningful interventions, but takes time to implement across diverse patient populations and departments. BPCI Advanced has proven to be a good platform from which to encourage change, giving Michigan Medicine a concrete set of conditions/surgeries for which to pilot certain interventions. For example, we have implemented Pharmacy Transition of Care calls for all Sepsis discharges, regardless of a patient's LACE score. Additionally, we have enhanced engagement from clinical champions, which leads to an interest in sharing data and setting goals for improvement.

The majority of Michigan Medicine's value-based payment models are now managed in the Quality Department, including BPCI Advanced. The Senior Director for Quality and the Chief Quality Officer will identify Quality Department staff to replace an individual who manages a particular program if he or she departs the organization. If an identified physician champion departs the organization, the BPCI Advanced Steering Committee would determine a replacement from the relevant Clinical Department.

The two main concerns from patients are the complex language used on the CMS-provided Beneficiary Notification letter, and the fear of additional cost-sharing related to participating in the program. Michigan Medicine has provided scripting to the care management staff who distribute the letters, and this has largely mitigated any negative feedback.

As a result of BPCI Advanced, there is an increased interest in reducing readmissions. While there has always been interest in this utilization measure from a patient outcomes and capacity management perspective, BPCI Advanced has added another financial benefit to impacting this measure beyond the other total cost of care programs in which we participate. Additionally, sharing data and increased messaging around appropriate post-acute utilization have changed culture around discharge disposition (e.g., discharging patients to home rather than a SNF) across the organization.

Michigan Medicine is acutely aware of the need to develop processes to identify unique risks attendant with BPCI-A participation.  We will be working to develop processes to monitor for these and other risks that could adversely impact BPCI-A beneficiaries.  We do note that Michigan Medicine maintains a robust compliance plan and we believe that many of the protections expressly stated in that compliance plan assure that BPCI beneficiaries receive medically necessary, timely, appropriate care.

In the event a manager departs the organization, the individuals senior manager will oversee all implementation duties in the interim. The senior manager will remove all access for the manager that departed the organization and will update any contact information as necessary. The senior manager will meet with the team involved in the implementation of the BPC Advanced Model to confirm if all deliverables and implementation are on track until an individual is hired and trained.

The initial CMS Beneficiary Notification letter contained our organization  phone number where the beneficiary can call if they had any questions. The theme of the questions we received are :- Beneficiary did not understand the letter and the initiative with Medicare - Beneficiaries wanted to know if there was this an an additional cost to them - Some beneficiaries reported, that when speaking with someone at Medicare to get more information about the model, the person with Medicare were not aware of the initiative.

Sound has developed a data analytic platform and clinical integration strategy to monitor and mitigate unintended consequences for our BPCIA patients.  We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. We have noticed that we do not receive all the notifications from CMS for each participant via email, whether it be general notifications, updates, or action items that are due in specific time-frame.  Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. We have noticed that we do not receive all the notifications from CMS for each participant via email, whether it be general notifications, updates, or action items that are due in specific time-frame.  Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. We have noticed that we do not receive all the notifications from CMS for each participant via email, whether it be general notifications, updates, or action items that are due in specific time-frame.  Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. We have noticed that we do not receive all the notifications from CMS for each participant via email, whether it be general notifications, updates, or action items that are due in specific time-frame.  Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

The senior manager will meet with the team involved in the implementation of the BPC Advanced Model to confirm if all deliverables and implementation are on track until an individual is hired and trained.

The initial CMS Beneficiary Notification letter contained our organization  phone number where the beneficiary can call if they had any questions. The theme of the questions we received are :- Beneficiary did not understand the letter and the initiative with Medicare - Beneficiaries wanted to know if there was this an an additional cost to them - Some beneficiaries reported, that when speaking with someone at Medicare to get more information about the model, the person with Medicare were not aware of the initiative.

Sound has developed a data analytic platform and clinical integration strategy to monitor and mitigate unintended consequences for our BPCIA patients.  We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. We have noticed that we do not receive all the notifications from CMS for each participant via email, whether it be general notifications, updates, or action items that are due in specific time-frame.  Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

The high priority redesign interventions include, but are not limited to:  identifying and addressing patients social determinants of health and behavioral health needs prior to the procedure, along with the specific needs/services relating directly to the procedure; partnering with local social service resources; partnering with discharge planners at acute facilities and with key post-acute providers to deliver the most appropriate levels of care and services to drive the best clinical outcome for the patient; incorporating clinical best practices into daily routines; improving communications and flow of information between patients/providers/caregivers throughout the episode of care.

Successes: Working directly with local resources, we have assisted patients in procuring housing, adequate food and transportation critical to an optimal clinical outcome.  Barriers: The current CMS retrospective funding model for the BPCI-A shared savings presents significant challenges when funding the additional resources necessary to implement the program successfully.

We continually meet with, educate and monitor each provider to ensure that all eligible patients are timely enrolled in the program and are meeting program requirements.  Providers sign attestations certifying that they are in compliance with the program.
We have not experienced any issues associated with submitting required documentation.

Retrospective (instead of prospective) based reimbursement structure puts enormous strain on non-convener participants funding cost of proper operations, care support, and in evaluating additional resources necessary to implement appropriate care and other non-covered requirements for the patients. For example, the lack of a list of CPT codes qualifying under each DRG that would trigger services.  Furthermore, the delay in confirming eligible episodes and proper bundles creates too much uncertainty, coupled with the fact that we do not have DRG level Target Pricing information for each ACH creates unnecessary challenges to make appropriate and timely value based care-cost decisions for each episode.

We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. Due to this, we would need to check each BPID to make sure that the "Action Item" notifications pertain to one or all. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

As a company comprised of 5 Regions under the same Tax ID, it took much collaboration and understanding of the BPCI Classic program to ensure our success with the BPCI Advanced program.  We have elected for several years now to (1) Pay our Direct Expenses first, (2) Pay the NPRA-Participating Physicians second and (3) Pay towards company overhead with any remaining funds.

Our process to monitor the Shared Repayment Amounts will be as follows:  (1) calculate the profit/loss from each reconciliation, (2) expect gains to be paid to the company and (3) expect losses to be subtracted out of future EOBs from CMS.  This is a simplified version since we are not convening for any other entity other than ourself.

We have created a BPCI committee which consists of 3 key administrative individuals.  Each person has been fully involved in the process of the program.  Should any one person leave the company, our plan is to have a succession plan in place with the remaining individuals to continue the program.  We also have an orientation program for new case managers that join the program to ensure the understanding of the program and the compliance requirements.Finally, we also have created a Physician Champion Task Force that meets as needed and is familiar with the program requirements.  This group of physicians has worked with both the BPCI Classic program as well as the BPCI Advanced program.  They are familiar with the data and program submission requirements.

Regular Communication touch points with the patient to ensure understanding of the program and to allow the patient to opportunity to communicate any concerns.Committee meeting to discuss the concerns from participants.Documentation of concerns to remain with the participation agreement.

Slow release of data early on with making a decision Retro drop (March 2019).  Should have had at least 3 months of data to make an informed decision.  Also, there needs to be a more clear way to easily identify patients that are associated with a Next Generation ACO.

Two significant achievements have been establishing a dedicated RN navigator to these patients, and both provider and community education on advance care planning.
Discharge destination planning is a challenge to make further improvements on as we have capacity and access issues in our market.

The high priority redesign interventions include, but are not limited to:  identifying and addressing patients social determinants of health and behavioral health needs prior to the procedure, along with the specific needs/services relating directly to the procedure; partnering with local social service resources; partnering with discharge planners at acute facilities and with key post-acute providers to deliver the most appropriate levels of care and services to drive the best clinical outcome for the patient; incorporating clinical best practices into daily routines; improving communications and flow of information between patients/providers/caregivers throughout the episode of care.

Successes: Working directly with local resources, we have assisted patients in procuring housing, adequate food and transportation critical to an optimal clinical outcome.  Barriers: The current CMS retrospective funding model for the BPCI-A shared savings presents significant challenges when funding the additional resources necessary to implement the program successfully.

Retrospective (instead of prospective) based reimbursement structure puts enormous strain on non-convener participants funding cost of proper operations, care support, and in evaluating additional resources necessary to implement appropriate care and other non-covered requirements for the patients. For example, the lack of a list of CPT codes qualifying under each DRG that would trigger services.  Furthermore, the delay in confirming eligible episodes and proper bundles creates too much uncertainty, coupled with the fact that we do not have DRG level Target Pricing information for each ACH creates unnecessary challenges to make appropriate and timely value based care-cost decisions for each episode.

CHF patients listed as first "high priority care redesign" because of readmit risks identified. We are doing ongoing collaborative work with cardiology/geriatric/pharmacy provider services clinics on patient touch points. CHF patients now followed through 90 day episodes with nursing care coordinator.  Fascia iliaca blocks started on Hip/Femur patients.  Anesthesiologist/ER providers trained.  Goals to reduce opioid use, constipation, delirium in hip/femur fracture patients.

Successes in addition to the CHF patient care and fascia iliaca blocks include IT building infrastructure for us to track our patients and assign risk levels for LOS and readmits that can be used by nursing care coordinators in following patients.  In addition, probable DRG codes by nursing review is moved to an MPage in Cerner so that patients can be met during their InPatient stay and given the guarantor letter and warm handoff to the nursing care coordinator.  Initial challenges on care redesign interventions have been around how to track the patients through the various EMR systems and creating a way to document the patients through their complete 90 day episodes.  Bringing understanding about the BPCI program and how it works has been somewhat resolved by created an easy to read explanation of the program to various clinics we are working with.  We have started meeting with the skilled nursing facilities after completing a quality scoring system for each based on their previous care of our Medicare patients to set up care expectations for our BPCI patients.

While not a formal plan, we have overlap in responsibilities on the BPCI-A  staffing that would allow the remaining team members to pick up responsibilities if one of our team members left the organization.  Our clinical team includes 3 RNs (Director, Manager, Staff Nurse) that are all familiar with the care management processes.  These nurses are further supported by a physician.  If any one of these nurses left, the others could pull together to keep our processes in place until a replacement could be found and hired.  On the administrative side, we have a Director and VP that share responsibilities which are also supported by a physician (same physician that supports the clinical area).

Our regular BPCI-A steering committee originally met on a bi-weekly basis and now meets monthly.  This committee consists of neuro science physicians, nurse practitioners, hospitalists, hospital administrators, care management, quality management and physical and occupational therapy. This working group has helped resolved several process issues that were impacting care for stroke patients that were part of the BPCI-A program as well as non-BPCI patients.  Providing data on utilization to the groups has spurred healthy discussion on how to make improvements on placing patients post discharge as well as how to avoid unnecessary ED visits and how to better manage patients that do return to the ED.

We review utilization data to identify unusual variations in patterns of care.  When unusual trends are identified, further research and/or analysis is conducted to better understand what has caused the change in utilization patterns and if these changes are reasonable.

We need to put this in place.  That said, the overwhelming amount of email and communication about BPCI-A makes it difficult to suss out what is urgent or has a deadline from simply informative information.  In the MSSP ACO program, we have a newsletter that highlights all important changes and we have a liaison that meets with us regularly by telephone to keep us on track of what needs to be done.  The ACO model for communication is much more effective.

Having a liaison (similar to MSSP) to be able to answer questions or provide information/explanation of program requirements would be helpful.The paperwork and contracting requirements are fairly overwhelming.It would be helpful to receive claims data on a more routine and timely basis.Having more benchmark data from CMS on how other participants are doing compared to our organization to help us identify areas for potential improvement would be helpful.

The Epic clinical EMR is very supportive of care being delivered for the initial acute episode, and for follow-up care by the AMI nurse navigator and care team, and into the physician offices of our collaborators.  We have developed the ability to get reports on all patients coded to an AMI DRG, who will thus be in the BPCI program.  Our AMI care team has gained great experience following patients across their 90 day episodes.  The cardiac physician champion, the cardiac clinical manager (a physician assistant) and the AMI navigator are all highly committed and now experienced.  In the last 5 months we have added a cardiac pharmacist, who handles discharge medication reconciliation on all AMI patients, and follows-up with them post-discharge.  We have also added a cardiac exercise physiologist who helps AMI patients craft individualized exercise programs.  We have clinical data support for analyzing the claims data.  The Executive Leadership Team is highly engaged at our BPCI Steering Council.

We are working on the CarePort EMR software that would notify us if patients get admitted elsewhere, but this module is not yet installed in several of the regional hospitals where our AMI patients get their local care. Thus unless patients tell us (and we do ask), we are not always aware of ER Visits and Readmissions to other hospitals, until we get the CMS claims data well after the care delivery.  The Telehealth patient tools have been not as robust as desired, nor as accepted by patients as hoped.  Addressing socio-economic barriers to care is an every day challenge.  There can be gaps in the post-acute collaboration (e.g. one patient spent 44 days in a SNF outside our state).

Our hospital and health system provide oversight and coverage for both Clinical Operations and Administrative Support specifically to the BPCI-Advanced Model.  There has been and continues to be broad transparency, collaboration and support in the work done by all teams working on this Program.

1. We have experienced great engagement of our Executive Leadership Team participating in the BPCI-Adv Steering Team with increased collaboration and understanding of patient care/work flows.2. For patients placed in the AMI Clinical Episode DRG, physicians have had difficulty amending the health record when the Final DRG is issued and that Final DRG is then not indicative for an AMI DRG (ie, upon further diagnostic testing, it is confirmed the patient did not experience an AMI) and before the patient discharge.

Our Executive Leadership Team is interfacing with our Direct Patient Care Team continuously and focusing on the Right Care at the Right Time for every patient (not just the AMI clinical episode).Regarding cost-shifting:  Our teams have also focused on demand-destruction of inpt rehabilitation and keeping patients in an inpt status to reduce costs.Our organization recently revised its Mission and Vision statement to reflect a sharper focus on consumers, overall health, and people's experience.  This update will guide our 2025 strategy called a 'Higher Mark'.  Some attributes of this statement:* High quality in every instance;* Accessible to everyone in every community we serve;* Affordable without ever sacrificing quality;* Worry-free at every touchpoint.Our vision is to be the catalyst that ignites a revolution in health care where everyone benefits from it.

There have been no barriers or challenges associated with submitting required documentation.  Any issues have been quickly amended by the BPCI-Adv Support Team.Overall, the design of the BPCI-Adv Portal works well from our perspective.

While a report was developed within our EMR to identify BPCI-Adv patients, there has been difficulty in successfully performing Advanced Care Planning (ACP), CPT 99497-99498. The challenges encompass the workflow (difficult to have discussion in every patient instance) and coding & documentation to support the coding requirements (discussion time length to meet of at least 30 minutes).If the patient is not expected to expire from an AMI and the clinician begins the ACP discussion, the patient may become scared of a 'death panel' and/or declines an ACP.  It can be a quick 2-minute discussion and does not meet the code's requirements to bill it.

We have developed an IT platform to collect data on each patient participating in the BPCIA program to monitor their next site of care, readmissions (all NSOC locations and root cause DRGs), SNF length of stay, SNF readmissions, use of high quality network agencies and facilities, and alignment with patient clinical desires of care with advance care planning.  We use our analytics to evaluate the outcomes of our patients in order to adjust our future interventions involving our physicians, nurses, care coordinating team, outpatient resources, and etc.  Our clinical team evaluates our patient care while in the acute setting and in the post acute setting for a 90 day window.  We have nurses, physicians, and care coordinators that link the care in the acute to the post acute setting to mitigate and monitor outcomes and possible unintended consequences.  This care team is integrated into our data and communication platforms to help drive performance and outcomes for each of our patients.

We have many active BPIDs as a participant. In this case, we received ACQ action items for 10 BPIDs, out of 78, but in reviewing the portal we need to submit for all 78 BPIDs.

The high priority redesign interventions include, but are not limited to:  identifying and addressing patients social determinants of health and behavioral health needs prior to the procedure, along with the specific needs/services relating directly to the procedure; partnering with local social service resources; partnering with discharge planners at acute facilities and with key post-acute providers to deliver the most appropriate levels of care and services to drive the best clinical outcome for the patient; incorporating clinical best practices into daily routines; improving communications and flow of information between patients/providers/caregivers throughout the episode of care.

Successes: Working directly with local resources, we have assisted patients in procuring housing, adequate food and transportation critical to an optimal clinical outcome.  Barriers: The current CMS retrospective funding model for the BPCI-A shared savings presents significant challenges when funding the additional resources necessary to implement the program successfully.

Positive outcomes- physicians are far more aware of, and involved in, their patients' post-acute care and recovery.
