Retrospective (instead of prospective) based reimbursement structure puts enormous strain on non-convener participants funding cost of proper operations, care support, and in evaluating additional resources necessary to implement appropriate care and other non-covered requirements for the patients. For example, the lack of a list of CPT codes qualifying under each DRG that would trigger services.  Furthermore, the delay in confirming eligible episodes and proper bundles creates too much uncertainty, coupled with the fact that we do not have DRG level Target Pricing information for each ACH creates unnecessary challenges to make appropriate and timely value based care-cost decisions for each episode.
NA; we didn't have any changes

Since October 1, 2018, care redesign initiatives have focused on ensuring that patients receive the right care, for the right reason, and for the right period of time during their episode of care.  This has meant assessing preoperative risk to drive optimization prior to surgery as well as purposeful comprehensive patient care management during the post-acute phase.  Care redesign is largely complete but will be ongoing throughout the program.

One of the biggest challenges with implementing care redesign is tracking progress and sharing information with pertinent parties.  Stryker has very successfully put in place systems to track progress in real time while utilizing retrospective claims data to drive actionable improvement.

One recent challenge with regard to executing agreements within Stryker's convener is executing non-financially based agreements with physicians and or non-physician practitioners.  There is very little reason from their perspective to spend their time reviewing, making potential changes to, and executing an agreement of this nature.  When an episode initiator is a hospital who has chosen not to gainshare financially downstream but is now required as of Q4 2019 to have non-financial participation agreements in place, it is very burdensome.
NA: System already in place before this model
NA; we don't have relationship with a BPCI Advanced Entity

As far as Stryker is concerned, financial arrangements and the ability to share savings is key to the success of bundled payment models.  It allows pertinent parties to align around shared vision and goals.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing
NA; not requiring shared repayments by partners

Stryker is a large BPCI Advanced convener and Performance Solutions has an impressive team of subject matter experts and consultants devoted solely to BPCI Advanced. When combined with our actuarial and analytics team, Stryker has approximately 60 staff members devoted to the program.  Succession planning is not an issue.

Most PGPs in Stryker's convener have chosen to provide a paper copy of the beneficiary notification form to patients in a pre-op educational packet prior to surgery.  Beneficiary notification is also provided electronically via RecoveryCOACH, Stryker's web based patient engagement and care management platform.

Medicare claims provided are monitored monthly for trends including readmission rates, emergency room use (diagnosis, day of the week, etc.), and complications.  If a negative trend is identified, the information is communicated back to all parties so that an action plan can be put into place. Episode initiators are routinely reminded that insufficient care may lead to higher cost and that the right care at the right time typically leads to cost reduction.

- New templates are provided by CMS every quarter for quarterly deliverables with little to no noticeable change- Documents have to be submitted quarterly regardless of whether there is no change from the previous submission- There is typically very little time given to complete a large set of deliverables.  This questionnaire is an example of that.  We have 2 weeks to submit the questionnaire and 3 corresponding documents for 70+ episode initiators, all with separate BPIDs and participation agreements.
NA; we didn't have any changes

Sutter Health's planned care improvement interventions for BPCI-A care episodes incorporate Lean process redesign to achieve better patient outcomes, higher patient satisfaction, and Medicare fee-for-service cost savings by improving care coordination and implementing more efficient, collaborative care. To date, Sutter's analysis of episodes of care within our system has revealed process variability in the utilization of skilled-nursing and acute-rehabilitation services that does not appear to be related to patient characteristics.Participation in the BPCI-A program is enabling Sutter to reexamine all aspects of episodic care, from pre-operative patient education through post-discharge home health and outpatient therapy, to standardizeour processes for ensuring each patient receives the appropriate level of post-acute care throughout the clinical episode.

Care Redesign interventions often involve third-party partnerships and collaborations, such as establishing standard orders with a diverse range of clinicians and post-acute care management protocols. While these collaborations are worthwhile, these also take time to achieve consensus and broad adoption.
The timeline for the BPCI Advanced Model has been significantly tight in terms of data availability, participation determination, episode selections, and establishing partner agreements.

A crucial consideration in establishing Financial Arrangements has been the fact that episode initiating physicians have expected upside-only arrangements in the current business environment, where the hospital systems face competition from private equity companies (as conveners) and physician groups themselves (as either conveners or non-conveners). This reality has presented challenges to effective alignment with episode initiators.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing
Sutter Health has hired a claims analytics vendor to assist with performance period reconciliations and NPRA calculations, including Shared Repayment Amounts.

To be clear, Sutter Health is not using MPP Waivers, but we are using the Fraud & Abuse waivers. Our compliance program would audit any sharing payment for compliance with the Fraud & Abuse, noting again we are not using the Medicare Payment Policy Waivers at this time.

Sutter Health has established an Executive Steering Committee to lead and monitor the BPCI Advanced program. This team of senior executives has direct accountability for the various functional areas necessary to effectively perform in value-based care and these senior executives provide an inherent succession plan to ensure ongoing engagement in this program.Furthermore, Sutter Health has a well-established succession planning process and tools to support leadership development and effectiveness across all functional areas within the enterprise.

Some Medicare beneficiaries are confused by the requirement to furnish the Beneficiary Notification Letter (BNL), as a subset of patients have considered this document a potential indication of substandard care as determined by CMS. Simply put, the BNL is confusing for some beneficiaries.

Each hospital team has formed workgroups to monitor current performance and discuss opportunities for variation reduction that aligns with the design of the BPCI Advanced program. This variation reduction work includes identifying and addressing unintended consequences associated with the implementation of the BPCI Advanced Model.
The timeline to respond to CMS documentation requirements is a challenge for a system this size, especially in light of the numerous stakeholders involved in a program with this scope.
NA; we didn't have any changes

At University Hospitals Health Systems (UH), we are dedicated to providing high quality care driven by evidence-based practices, patient engagement, coordination of care, and care transitions. The UH BPCIA team has engaged the High Reliability Medicine staff to collaborate with  Division Chiefs of 21 disease groups in order to standardize clinical pathway guidelines, EMR ordersets, delivery of care, patient education, and primary care physician education. In addition, hospital ancillary teams have been engaged in order to create standardized patient mobility scoring systems to assist in discharging patients to the appropriate next site of care and to begin early ambulation in hopes of minimizing deconditioning. Last, multiple oversight committees and project teams have been established to lead and monitor operations, quality and safety, as well as patient education.

We are impressed by the excitement, and engagement, of clinical teams and ACH Episode Initiator leadership. There has been a great deal of collegial spirit as our subject matter experts focus on enhancing acute care delivered to our patients as well as ensuring patients are discharged to the appropriate location to further their healing. We are excited when considering the efforts being placed in redesigning our care plans and standardizing processes across the health system. To us, the witnessed dedication and desire to improve patient outcomes is truly a success.

The biggest challenge experienced is simply the lack of BPCIA education amongst partners. To mitigate this challenge, our team visits each ACH facility quarterly to share critical program information and education that has been created to detail agreement and quality requirements. A BPCIA community site, for the purpose of education, has been created internally at the UH Digital Workplace, and bi-weekly meetings have been held with Division Chiefs to assist in delivery of accurate details to their physician teams. In addition, the Medical Director of BPCIA frequently engages with physicians and ACH partners to share updates for process and procedure while the Administrative Director collaborates to share financial updates as well as post-acute utilization metrics.Another challenge has been the requirement that we enter Participating Practitioner Agreement for providers that we designate as QPPs.  With 37 episode combinations across 9 hospitals, we have many providers involved in our BPCIA program.  It is very difficult to obtain agreements with all of the providers.  We would prefer a process were we provide a notice to the provider, educating them about the BPCIA program, and the fact that we intend to include them on the QPP list.  At that point, they could choose to opt out and we would not include them on the list.
NA; never participated in financial arrangements
NA; we don't participate in NPRA Sharing
No comments at this time as we are not NPRA sharing.
NA; we don't participate in NPRA Sharing
No comments at this time as we are not NPRA sharing.

UH leadership thoughtfully weighed the pros and cons of entering the voluntary BPCIA initiative. After much consideration, willingness to assume financial risk stemmed from our experience in other value based payment models such as Medicare Shared Savings and BPCI. Prior to BPCIA, our team established communications and care coordination efforts with physicians and post-acute providers including primary care providers and community resources. Further, we established a care management structure that allowed for the identification of high risk patients, tracking of the patient's status across the episode and care coordination with an assigned clinical resource (e.g. patient navigator) for the duration of the bundle. All of these efforts were designed to focus on improving beneficiary outcomes and experience, and used to influence policy and practice within our organization. We continue to work with our post-acute and community partners in the development of common practices and processes.
NA; we don't participate in ICS Sharing
NA; not using any of the waivers

At University Hospitals, we recognize the "Next Man Up" methodology. Each member of our team is highly involved, ready and willing to get the collective job done no matter what the set-back could be. While we have a small team at this time, our newest employees have been offered opportunities to take on critical, game-changing assignments forcing them to think outside-the-box in an effort to learn program requirements and adhere to the Participant Agreement. We realize the bottom line is important; however, teamwork is the most critical component to our success. With this in mind, all have been provided with appropriate cross-training, shadowing, and project leadership opportunities in order to provide a well-balanced experience in the event a member of the team departs the organization.

Change is hard, and to be honest, we were expecting a great deal of resistance from system-wide physicians, leaders, and hospital staff when implementing workflow changes in support of the BPCIA initiative. We have been pleasantly surprised by the thoughtful participation of our colleagues as we all strive to improve patient outcomes and build framework for care processes. Being highly visible, and taking a caring approach, our team has been used as the "sounding board" for staff and physician concerns; I believe this results from our ability to build meaningful relationships of trust and transparency, which have proven to be highly respected despite the information delivered to our colleagues being negative at times. When negative communication has been delivered, we have witnessed a competitive spirit emerge resulting in teams brainstorming to quickly resolve identified problems...a bit of friendly rivalry throughout the health system. And...we have witnessed UH ACHs struggling with BPCIA performance seeking help, which is always hard to do.

The BPCIA and High Reliability Medicine (HRM) teams have created weekly process and monthly outcomes scorecards to monitor the performance of 21 disease processes across the UH health system. The process scorecards provide a weekly visual of performance by facility and disease group and encompass reduction in skilled nursing usage using evidence-based mobility assessment prior to discharge, increasing in Home w/ or w/out Home Health support for those patients who should be discharged home, and ensuring patients are following up with their physicians within seven days of discharge to enforce medication adherence, mitigate disease process concerns, and reduce readmissions. The monthly scorecards focus on 30- and 90-day patient outcomes relating to length of stay, mortality, readmissions, and cost. In addition, an interactive BPCIA quality dashboard is currently being created to track all BPCIA quality metrics to ensure we mitigate unintended consequence of the model.
NA; we have not yet implemented a system for monitoring and responding to beneficiary complaints
NA; no complaint monitoring system yet

We have experienced a few barriers associated with BPCIA documentation:1. QPP templates are not user friendly, and we find it is difficult to add rows within already completed rows and columns when edits are necessary.2. At times, the Innovation Portal is slow when trying to upload and/or download documents.

A suggestion:It would be beneficial to schedule additional webinars for participants to discuss ongoing changes to the BPCIA program. Numerous emails have been sent from CMS regarding the program this year, all of which are confusing in one way or the other, and leave us wondering what is being asked of our team. In addition, we are finding it challenging to receive timely responses from the CMS Innovation team especially when the ask for clarification is attached to a submission deadline. Could be improvement in this process as well.

While in our care redesign plan we identified that most areas we already had interventions "in place." We continuously monitor and re-asses our care delivery through regular meetings with stakeholders. Two significant achievements have been establishing a dedicated RN navigator to these patients, and both provider and community education on advance care planning.
Discharge destination planning is a challenge to make further improvements on as we have capacity and access issues in our market.
NA; we are a Non-Convener Participant

We have not entered into any agreements with practitioners at this time. There has been significant movement of medical staff in the last two years and need to finalize who our provider partners will be moving forward.

Stryker is a large BPCI Advanced convener and Performance Solutions has an impressive team of subject matter experts and consultants devoted solely to BPCI Advanced. When combined with our actuarial and analytics team, Stryker has approximately 60 staff members devoted to the program.  Succession planning is not an issue.

Most PGPs in Stryker's convener have chosen to provide a paper copy of the beneficiary notification form to patients in a pre-op educational packet prior to surgery.  Beneficiary notification is also provided electronically via RecoveryCOACH, Stryker's web based patient engagement and care management platform.

Medicare claims provided are monitored monthly for trends including readmission rates, emergency room use (diagnosis, day of the week, etc.), and complications.  If a negative trend is identified, the information is communicated back to all parties so that an action plan can be put into place. Episode initiators are routinely reminded that insufficient care may lead to higher cost and that the right care at the right time typically leads to cost reduction.

Through the system-wide transitions of care program, we have embedded transitions of care nurses in all the medical centers. We have also created a process to ensure all bpci advanced patients are identified and connected to the right resource. Finally, we developed a team of post acute care liaisons to follow patients, support warm hand-offs/transitions after the inpatient discharge.

Some successes include: increasing awareness of value based care programs across the organization and improving operational integration and coordination among various clinical departments. Some challenges include: short time frame to analyze large quantities of data and some of the attribution overlap with various CMS value based care programs (CJR and ACO).
We had a system-wide Epic implementation for all the hospitals in 2018.
There have been no material challenges.

NWMHP has made progress with identifying trends to support both provider and beneficiary communication with transitions of care and development of care pathways.  Pathways are currently in review with cardiology input for bundles selected to include a review of rehospitalizations and contributing factors for provider education.  NWMHP has created and shared score cards with improved outcomes related to appropriate level care, assistance with care coordination, and education regarding Advance Care Planning.

Barriers: 1)  Beneficiary engagement for 90 day post-discharge to support education for self-care and social determinants of health support due to limited awareness of who NWMHP ACO is.   2) Non-participating provider engagement. Successes: 1) NWMHP, in partnership with our participants, reduced SNF utilization from 54% of discharges to 46% by supporting safe discharges to home and warm handoffs.   2) NWMHP has developed analytics to map out our outcomes and to analyze our strategies for success.  We have not fully met our goals however we are able to identify where we are improving and what trends we have opportunities to address.

We have not implemented any waivers for the BPCI Advanced program however have identified the benefit.  To implement the waivers within the BPCI Advanced program further analysis of workflow's for accuracy with identifying participating beneficiaries is required.

NW Momentum has informal workflows in place explaining required documentation processes and procedures, as well as day to day operational scope. These informal workflows are currently being refined and converted to formal procedures.

Trending of care and services provided within the NGACO population and the BPCI Advanced population are compared and monitored for outcomes and appropriate discharge planning and services to support health outcomes.
